In addition to the nuclear power plants and the reprocessing plants at Sellafield, there is a demonstration plant for the production of so-called MOX fuel. A permanent factory for MOX fuel production got licensed in October 2001. There is a one operative vitrification plant at Sellafield to transform radioactive waste, and BNFL also runs a transport company for the transport of spent nuclear fuel to Sellafield.<br>
<br>
MOX Demonstration Facility (MDF)<br>
Since 1993, BNFL-Sellafield has run a small factory that produces Mixed Oxide Fuel (MOX) known as the MOX Demonstration Facility (MDF). MOX fuel produced at this facility has been delivered to customers in Switzerland and Germany.<br>
<br>
In the autumn of 1999, an agreement was made to deliver MOX fuel to the Japanese company Kansai Electric Power Company. The first transport of MOX was shipped to Japan in July 1999. However, in September of the same year, it was discovered that the safety analyses of BNFL’s MOX fuel had been falsified, and by December it became clear that this also applied to the fuel that had been delivered to Japan. Consequently, Kansai Electric Power Company refused to use the fuel, and demanded that BNFL should take it back immediately. At the same time the Japanese government issued a temporary restraint on all business relations with BNFL.<br>
<br>
In March 2000, the Swiss Nuclear Safety Inspectorate (HSK) also discovered insufficient safety information about the MOX pellets in the fuel delivered by BNFL-Sellafield. Prior to this, a weakness in the cladding of the MOX fuel delivered by BNFL to the Swiss Beznau reactor, was discovered. In view of this defect, HSK forbade all import and use of MOX fuel from BNFL. Even before this, the country had instituted a moratorium against the export of fuel to Sellafield. HSK said that BNFL would have to show “substantial improvements” before the prohibitions possibly would be called off.<br>
<br>
During the exposure of the scandal, British nuclear inspectors discovered that operators at MDF had been falsifying safety analyses of the fuel since 1996. In a report from the British Nuclear Installations Inspectorate (NII), it was asserted that BNFL had “a serious safety culture problem” and “systematic management failure”.<br>
<br>
The scandal resulted in also Germany prohibiting any further import of MOX from Sellafield. Germany had also instituted a moratorium on reprocessing fuel at Sellafield, after German radiation authorities discovered enhanced radiation values on the outside of BNFL’s transport bottles. Internally the scandal led to several dismissals, as well as a reconsideration of all former safety procedures. Furthermore, BNFL’s chief executive, John Taylor, resigned from his position. Today the entire factory is shut down with little likelihood of ever being reopened for commercial MOX production. <br>
<br>
In 1999, Sweden had planned to reprocess 4.8 tonnes of spent reactor fuel from its first research reactor R1 at Sellafield. However, in the wake of the falsification scandal, the Swedish minister for the environment, Kjell Larsson, stated that a business deal with Sellafield would be “very difficult, if not impossible” to legitimate. <br>
<br>
In April 2001, Germany lifted its moratorium on reprocessing at Sellafield, and Switzerland followed suit in May. Transports of spent fuel to Sellafield have therefore recently been resumed; however, the moratoria on the use of BNFL MOX have been retained. <br>
<br>
BNFL has agreeed with NII that MDF will in future only be used as a research facility.<br>
<br>
Sellafield Mox-Plant (SMP)<br>
In 1996, BNFL opened the Sellafield Mox Plant (SMP), a new and much larger MOX factory with an annual production capacity of 120 tonnes of MOX fuel. The factory cost £482 million to realise. SMP today has been through a test period during which it produces regular quantities of uranium oxide fuel.<br>
<br>
By the end of 2000, the factory had produced 150,000 UO2 pellets. (One fuel rod consists of several such pellets.) BNFL was in October 2001 given a permit from the authorities to use plutonium oxide in order to start up MOX production. Because reprocessed uranium and plutonium from THORP will be utilised in the production of MOX, the factory is crucial to future operations at the entire Sellafield plant. A new report made by Oxford Research Group on the commission of the British Ministry of Environment states that it would be quite easy for terrorists to make bombs out of stolen MOX. Based on the report, several experts have advised against granting the new MOX factory a licence. Michael Sadnicki, a member of the Government’s work group on the management of spent reactor fuel, believes that it makes very little economic sense to produce MOX, and he goes on to point out that the mere process of putting the factory into operation may easily exceed £300 million.<br>
<br>
The new factory is also struggling to access contracts for the delivery of MOX fuel. After the discovery in the autumn of 1999, that BNFL had been falsifying the safety analyses of MOX fuel since 1996, all the major customers in Japan, Germany and Switzerland imposed a ban on the import of BNFL-produced MOX. Following renegotiations with BNFL, Japan has however lifted this ban. However, in the spring of 2001, yet another dispute arose when people living in close proximity to Japan’s biggest nuclear power plant, , voted in a referendum against the use of MOX in the reactor. BNFL neverthless claims that it has accessed 40 percent of the contracts needed in order to run the plant for the first ten years.<br>
<br>
However, many of the contracts are with German companies, and Germany is not yet willing to lift the ban against the import of BNFL-MOX. Even if the German ban should be removed, BNFL still stands the risk of losing some, or even all of these contracts. If this should happen, there is very little market left to justify the implementation of a factory for new MOX production. An independent report commissioned by the British government shows that in the coming ten years, SMP at best will only be able to earn £216 million for the £460 million it took building the plant. <br>
<br>
The Irish government has protested strongly against the new plant, and on June 13, 2001, Ireland brought charges against the United Kingdom in an international court of law on grounds of violating international regulations on the conveyance of information. The Irish minister for nuclear safety, Joe Jacob, said that the British government had withheld vital information to analyses concerning the necessity of opening the factory.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
